{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dd5b601-7b7f-44a5-aaa6-07b2ed45f07a","content":"For a **.NET Web API**, use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n### Example:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --name MyApi\n```\n\nFor **JWT bearer auth** without Azure AD, start with `--auth None` and add `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` manually.\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` for all available options in your SDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a95aa10b-97ac-4625-b020-839556e5b0ce","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context) or possibly other frameworks. Let me answer based on my knowledge without needing to search the codebase, as this is a general development question.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about common web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":283,"requestId":"4022:15632C:46CE36:52174F:69F00426"},"id":"eea5fdf2-fcec-4bd9-aa4e-be7574d0b0b9","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:49:51.292Z","parentId":"e79a0eaf-5322-4350-82aa-20c1d3380703"}
